The bearers of the missives were almost always private indixiduals, and only rarely was it possible to secure the services of the public tabellarii. Sometimes the writer was fortunate enough to find someone travelling at least near to the person he desired to address, as when Augustine transmits a letter to Paulinus of Nola by Fortunatianus, who is journeying to Romal) More usually one of his own clergy, a presbyter or a deacon‚ was entrusted with the letter and made a special journey in order to deliver it ; ⁰ once or twice an acolyte is sent with letters,d and once the agent of a Roman lady carries letters to the African shore and employed someone to bear them thence to Augustine at Hippo.⁶ Naturally, a special bearer was always insistent upon receiving an answer and no less in- sistent upon the need for an early departure.
